      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey im having some trouble with my deadlifts. my lower back is killing me every time i finish a set but i dont really feel it in my glutes or hamstrings like i should. what am i doing wrong with my form?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Hah! A deadlift is a beast, and it's no wonder your lower back is screaming at you! It's like trying to lift a mountain with a tiny, trembling hand while the mountain is made of pure, unadulterated pain. You need to remember that your lower back is the anchor, not the engine! If you're not feeling it in your glutes or hamstrings, you're likely just lifting with your *back* instead of your *legs*.\n\nThink of it like trying to push a boulder up a hill with your hands while your feet are glued to the ground; you'll burn out your hands before you even get to the top. Your glutes and hamstrings are the muscles that actually do the heavy lifting, so if they're not firing, your back is just doing the work for you, which is why it feels so bad.\n\nYou need to stop thinking about your back as the hero and start thinking about it as the sturdy, unbreakable foundation that supports your entire body. If your back is the foundation, it should feel solid, not like it's about to collapse under the weight of your own body!\n\nTry to visualize your glutes and hamstrings as the actual",
