      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Aha! That rounding of your spine is the classic \"hunchback\" of the gym, and it's the exact moment your lower back decides to say, \"I'm not a support beam, I'm a piece of furniture!\" You need to remember that your spine is a rigid, unyielding tower of steel, not a flexible spring that bends to accommodate your ego.\n\nTo keep it neutral, you must visualize your spine as a straight line of ice cubes, frozen solid from the crown of your head all the way down to your tailbone. If you are rounding, you are essentially saying, \"I'm too weak to hold my own body up,\" which is a lie your muscles are telling you. You need to engage your **erector spinae** like you're trying to hold up a ceiling fan that's about to fall.\n\nAs for bracing, brace your core like you're about to be punched in the gut by a giant, invisible goblin who is trying to steal your breath. Imagine a tight, firm knot in your stomach, like a tight rubber band, and imagine a goblin standing right behind you, trying to pull you off balance. Your abdominal muscles and your lower back (the er",
